The genus Copris Geoffroy, 1762
is globally distributed with currently more than 235 species formally being described (
Davis et al . 2008
). Over a third of all species have been recorded in the Palaearctic and Oriental Region ( Balthasar 1963 ;
Davis et al . 2008
). The genus Copris is commonly divided into four subgenera: Copris , ParacoprisBalthasar, 1939 , MicrocoprisBalthasar, 1958 and SinocoprisOchi, Kon & Bai, 2009 according to morphological characters of the elytra and the pronotum ( Balthasar 1939 , 1958 , 1963 ;
Ochi et al . 2009
). Many of Asian Copris species have been only recently discovered and described (
Ochi et al . 2004
, 2008 , 2009 , 2018 , 2019a ,b;
Bui et al . 2018
). Yet, we still have an incomplete understanding of these taxa, especially in the subgenus Paracopris with only six species being described since the work of Balthasar (1939) (for details see Checklist). Currently, the subgenus Paracopris consists of 24 species, of which 21 are the Asian species ( Arrow 1931 ; Balthasar 1963 ; Ochi & Kon 1996 ; Kabakov & Napolov 1999 ; Kabakov & Shokhin 2014 ;
Hanboonsong et al . 2003
; Sewak 2009 ; Shahabuddin 2010 ;
Bai et al . 2011
;
Sabu et al . 2011
;
Cheung et al . 2018
;
Ochi et al . 2019a
,b). Only three species have been recorded in Africa, comprising Copris ( Paracopris ) bihamatusBalthasar, 1965 from South Africa ( Balthasar 1965 ), C . ( P .) ciprianiiBalthasar, 1939 from Zambia(Nguyen-Phung 1988 ; Bezděk & Hájek 2012 ) and C . ( P .) simil- isBalthasar, 1939 from the Democratic Republic of the Congo , Zimbabwe and the Union of South Africa (Nguyen- Phung 1988). The subgenus Paracopris is well separated from the other subgenera of the genus Copris in the elytral surface and pronotal structure. While the strongly punctate elytra of Paracopris clearly differentiate them from the subgenus Microcopris , the anteriorly untruncated pronotum of Paracopris spp. differentiates them from the subgenera Sinocopris and Copris sensu stricto . Paracopris , despite being the distinct subgenus, is particularly problematic, due to only minute morphological differences in the elytral and pygidial punctures between species, coupled with significant intraspecific morphological variation within the species of the subgenus. These poorly defined morphological boundaries pose major problems for the delineation and identification of Copris ( Paracopris )
species. In order to enable reliable species identification, we morphologically re-examined the Asian Copris species deposited in the Muséum National d’Histoire Naturelle (Paris, France ) and the National Museum ( Prague , Czech Republic ), and found one previously undescribed Copris species from Java ( Indonesia ). This species could be assigned to the subgenus Paracopris due to the possession of distinctly punctate elytral intervals and an anteriorly untruncated pronotum. The external morphology of the undescribed species bears much resemblance to Copris ( Paracopris ) punctulatusWiedemann, 1823 , especially in the upwards protruded clypeal apex, but it consistently differs from the latter by a densely, but separately punctate pygidium. More importantly, morphological differences of the aedeagi clearly separate both species. In the following, we describe the new species from Java , and re-describe its resembling species C. ( P. ) punctulatus , including detailed illustrations of both sexes and the male genitalia. In addition, we designate a neotype of C. ( P. ) punctulatus as the type specimen was lost. We complement these descriptions and the neotype designation with a first checklist of the Asian members of the subgenus Paracopris along with new data on the distribution of the known Asian species.

