sec.p:
Limited access to the scattered museum specimens combined with poorly defined species boundaries within the subgenus Paracopris created obstacles for taxonomic work, and led to the neglection of the subgenus for many years. Increasing interest in Asian dung beetle taxonomy and ecology (
Hayes et al . 2009
; Senior 2012;
Raine et al . 2018
;
Ochi et al . 2019a
, b) created a need to re-examine existing collections and to identify reliable morphological characters to delineate species boundaries in the subgenus Paracopris . By comparing various morphological traits of different Paracopris species, we determined the clypeal apex, the anterior pronotal margin and the structure of clypeal, pronotal, elytral intervals, as well as pygidial and femoral punctures as potentially important morphological traits to confine species boundaries in the subgenus Paracopris . The discovery of Copris ( P. ) javanensisnew species increases the number of known species of Paracopris to 24, of which 21 have been exclusively recorded from Asia. Only three species have been recorded out of Asia: Copris ( Paracopris ) bihamatusBalthasar, 1965 from the north east highlands of South Africa along the eastern escarpment ( Balthasar 1965 ); C. ( P. ) ciprianiiBalthasar, 1939 (later synonymized with Copris coriarius Gillet, 1907
) from Zambia , and C. ( P. ) similisBalthasar, 1939 (subsequently synonymized with Copris mesacanthus mesacanthus Harold, 1878
) from the Democratic Republic of the Congo , Zimbabwe , Transvaal Province, Province of Natal and Cape Province of the Union of South Africa(Nguyen-Phung 1988 ; Bezděk & Hájek 2012 ). This suggests that the subgenus Paracopris has its central distribution in Asia and that current sampling efforts are likely far from comprehensive. Further studies focusing on the Asian Paracopris species seem indispensable to improve our knowledge on the diversity, evolution and distribution of this subgenus.
